Because I have some bills that need paid, I am selling my SMLE No4 MK1 rifle along with the 780 rounds of .303 ammo I have for it.

The rifle was an early import to the US (it has no importer marks). As per the markings on the gun and the serial, I am pretty sure it is a Maltby arsenal rifle. This rifle shows its age/character but functions like it should. The battle peep on the ladder sight is slightly bent as shown in the included pictures.

As for the ammo:

There are 30 rounds of Greek HXP ammo on stripper clips. The primers are not corrosive and the brass is reloadable. The ammo comes with the original bandolier and the 4 empty stripper clips. 

There remaining 750 rounds are Iraqi head stamped rounds on stripper clips, in 15 bandoliers. The Arabic head stamps show manufacture date of 1956. This ammo is cordite and corrosively primed so the brass is NOT reloadable. This ammo has some corrosion on it because of storage conditions. Most of it should fine to fire but there are small amount of casings that look like they may have some pitting and should not be fired. The stripper clips show more problems than the ammo itself because of metal types. Some of the strippers are serviceable, some are probably not.  Iraqi surplus ammo is collectible and bullets could be pulled from casings so there is still value even in the questionable ammo.

I am asking $650obo for the rifle plus ammo.
I am willing to consider cash plus partial trades.

I will need to see your IN Driver’s License and preferably your carry permit. I am located in Kosciusko County. If you can’t meet me within a reasonable distance (hour drive of Warsaw), let me know so can figure out shipping costs to your local FFL.

title: For Sale:  WTT/WTS Vepr 7.62x39 16", PPS-43, 7.62x39 andx54R ammo
postcontent:
What the title says.

If you don't know what a Vepr is, it's the best Russian-made AK you can get your hands on (the photo is stock obviously). You need to install a bullet guide if you want to use hicap mags, but it's literally an hour of work and I have the thing in the mail.

PPS-43 is a Polish copy of the best SMG of WWII. Considered a handgun (stock welded closed), so with a CCW you can take it camping into national parks and such. The 7.62x25 round makes it a lot more manageable than similar AK pistols. 4x35 round mags with it.

The ammo is good combloc surplus in 1000+ round amounts, also low-recoil hollow core Czech 7.62x54 and a 640 tin of commercial 7.62x39 Brown Bear. I also have a few various Mosins, Rossi .22 revolver, CZ52, SKS stocks, kevlar helmet, Glock 33 round mag etc.etc., basically a lot of trade fodder, with more cool firearms available for good trades.

-----------

I'm looking mostly for old military rifles and handguns. Must be either common caliber (e.g. 7.62x54), or at least an obtainable caliber (e.g. 7.5 Swiss, not 8mm Steyr stuff). Specifically, I'm interested in: 
- SVT40, Vepr/AK54R, PSL. Basically a battle rifle in 7.62x54. In that order of preference. 
- Lahti pistol, especially Finn Lahti. 
- Broomhandle mauser. 
- 7.62x25 ammo. 
- Vepr 12. 12ga shotguns in general. 
- .22 rifle. 
- Russian SKSes. 
- Slidefire/bumpski AK stocks. 
- SKS bullpup stocks. 

Also interested in other battle rifles (not terribly interested in stuff like .308 - the current crisis moved it into $1/round area, might as well use .50), military handguns, bolt-actions, and other cool stuff. Shoot me an offer, worst I can say is no.

--------

I will take cash offers. But - look at what other people are asking on Gunbroker/here for the same item, on average, then offer me ten-fifteen percent less and we can haggle. Lowballs will be politely declined.

Best wishes,
Daniel

postcontent:
1944 Izzy M38 Mosin-Nagant Carbine 
All numbers matching. Magazine does have a single strike from arsenal for a match.
Counter bored from arsenal.
TRUE M38 STOCK!!!! NOT A M38 IN A M44 STOCK.
Good physical condition with some markings on the wood.
Sling.

More on the rare side!!! Only 167,000 produced in 1944. Compared to over 400k in '41, over 680k in '42, and over 970K in '43; according to author Terence W. Lapin.

Model 1938 Carbine: A carbine based on the M1891/30 design that was produced from 1939 to 1945 at the Izhevsk arsenal and in 1940 and 1944 at Tula. They were intended for use by second-echelon and noncombatant troops. Essentially a M1891/30 with a shortened barrel and shortened stock (the M38 is 40 inches (1,000 mm) in overall length versus 48 inches overall length for the Model 91/30), this carbine did not accept a bayonet; was in fact designed so the standard Model 91/30 bayonet would not fit it. However many M38 carbines were fitted into M44 stocks by the Soviets as a wartime expedient. M38s in the correct M38 stock command a premium over M38s in M44 pattern stocks. The M38 was replaced by the M44 carbine in 1944

Anderson Manufacturing, a machine shop that rescued its operations by entering the business of designing and manufacturing AR-15 style rifles, now offers five different models of rifles for hunting, target shooting, and military/police applications.

Designated with the “AM” (Anderson Manufacturing) moniker to set them apart from traditional “AR” (Armalite Rifle) models, Anderson Manufacturing rifles offer design and build quality that exceeds that of other firearms manufacturers around the world along with RF-85, a proprietary metal treatment.

Anderson Manufacturing employs a proprietary metal treatment for all its rifles that reduces friction on all the steel surfaces by 85%, resulting in a more efficient and reliable weapon. Known as RF-85 (reduce friction 85%), the treatment offers significant benefits such as faster cycle rates and cooler operating temperatures. This results in significantly less wear on the weapon, thereby increasing its life. In addition, an RF-85 treated weapon does not need any lubricants.
